"{\n    \"introduction\": \"The Whiskey Rebellion of 1794 was a pivotal event in solidifying federal authority and influencing the development of American political parties. The uprising was sparked by a federal excise tax on whiskey, which frontier farmers saw as unfair and oppressive, leading to violent protests. The rebellion's suppression by President Washington reinforced federal power and highlighted differences in political ideology, contributing to the formation of political parties that would shape American politics.\",\n    \"name\": \"Whiskey Rebellion Aftermath\",\n    \"description\": \"The rebellion's suppression delineated ideological divisions, catalyzing the evolution of America's first political party system.\",\n    \"dates\": [\"1794\", \"1794\"],\n    \"effects\": [\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Federalist Party Ascendancy\",\n        \"score\": 8\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Democratic-Republican Mobilization\",\n        \"score\": 9\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Alien and Sedition Acts\",\n        \"score\": 7\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Fries's Rebellion\",\n        \"score\": 6\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Election of 1796\",\n        \"score\": 5\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Virginia and Kentucky Resolutions\",\n        \"score\": 7\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Formation of Party Caucuses\",\n        \"score\": 8\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Hamilton's Economic Policies Scrutinized\",\n        \"score\": 6\n      }\n    ],\n    \"conclusion\": \"The Whiskey Rebellion was a significant turning point in the early United States, underscoring the contentious issues of federal taxation and governance. The event set the stage for further political division and the establishment of organized parties that would dominate the political landscape.\",\n    \"people\": [\n      \"George Washington\",\n      \"Alexander Hamilton\",\n      \"Thomas Jefferson\",\n      \"James Mad